It’s a summation of all your assets (things you own), your liabilities (what you owe to others), and what the bottom line is (your net worth) after everything is settled. Here’s an example of a simple balance sheet for an individual: John Smith – Personal Balance Sheet As of 12/31/20XX Assets Cash (Checking and Savings) $1,000 Car 10,000 Home 250,000 Retirement 401(k) 50,000 Stocks 10,000 Total 321,000 Liabilities Car Loan 5,000 Home Mortgage 150,000 Student Loans 25,000 Credit Card Debt 5,000 Total 185,000 Net Worth 136,000 Net Worth Percent 42% Note that the Assets must equal Liabilities plus net worth (or owner’s equity, as it is referred to on a business’ balance sheet). In other words, it must balance, and that’s why it’s called a Balance Sheet. 4/10/2020
